         <abstract>
            <p>Over two hundred years ago, Waring raised the question of representing natural integers as sums of integral $k$th powers. At the beginning of this century, Hilbert proved that, for any fixed $k$, the minimal number of summands needed in the representation of any integer can be uniformly bounded. The least such bound is denoted by $g(k)$. A first goal is to show that our knowledge of $g(k)$ is rather satisfactory: -Writing down all the numbers $g(2), g(3),\ldots, g(K)$ may be performed in $O(K^2)$ bit operations, which is best possible, since $g(k)$ has $(k + 1)$ digits in its binary expansion. -Writing down $g(k)$ may be performed in $O(k \log k \log \log k)$ bit operations, which we expect to be fairly close to the actual complexity. A second aim is to discuss the complexity of checking the validity of the conjectured Diophantine inequality $$\{(3/2)^k\} \leq 1 - (3/4)^k;$$ the underlying idea has led J. M. Kubina and M. C. Wunderlich to check this up to 471,600,000. This inequality is related to Waring's problem in that it would imply the formula $$g(k) = 2^k + \lbrack(3/2)^k\rbrack - 2;$$ however, the knowledge of this relation would not improve our knowledge on the complexity of computing $g(k)$, neither on average, nor for individual values of $k$.</p>
          </abstract>
